<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-07-27T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-07-27T08:00:00-05:00" n="709" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d709">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1981</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-07-27T13:00:00+00:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">July 27, 1915, 1 p. m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11.40 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>2536. The public and private and official and unofficial comment on
                                our latest note to Germany is practically unanimous in approval.
                                Most of it is of very hearty commendation. The very general opinion,
                                as far as I can gather it, is that war is inevitable between the
                                United States and Germany. Nobody seems to believe that Germany will
                                meet our demands nor that she will cease her unlawful submarine
                                acts.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>